{{confused|Flatpack}} {{Infobox software | name = Flatpak | title = Flatpak | logo = Flatpak.png | logo caption = | logo size = | logo alt = | screenshot = | caption = | screenshot size = | screenshot alt = | collapsible = | author = | developer = Alex Larsson, Flatpak Team | released = {{Start date and age|2015|09|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web | url = https://github.com/flatpak/flatpak/wiki/Flatpak's-History | title = Flatpak's History | website = GitHub}}</ref> | discontinued = | latest release version = 1.0.6 | latest release date = {{Start date and age|2018|11|16|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web | url = https://github.com/flatpak/flatpak/releases | title = Releases · flatpak/flatpak | website = GitHub}}</ref> | latest preview version = | latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | programming language = [[C (programming language)|C]] | operating system = [[Linux]] | platform = | size = | language = | language count = <!-- Number only --> | language footnote = | genre = [[Application virtualization]] | license = [[LGPL]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cgit.freedesktop.org/xdg-app/xdg-app/tree/COPYING|title=LGPL|website=''xdg-app repository''<!-- de-italicized because description, not name -->|publisher=freedesktop.org|accessdate=2016-11-21}}</ref> | website = {{URL|flatpak.org}}}}
'''Flatpak''' (formerly '''xdg-app''') is a [[software utility]] for [[software deployment]], [[package management]], and [[application virtualization]] for [[Linux#Desktop|Linux desktop]] computers. It provides a [[Sandbox (computer security)|sandbox]] environment in which users can run [[Application software|applications]] in isolation from the rest of the system.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.gnome.org/alexl/2016/04/29/using-bubblewrap-in-xdg-app/ |title=Using bubblewrap in xdg-app |date=29 April 2016 |website=Alexander Larsson: Cool links and commentary |publisher=GNOME |first=Alexander |last=Larsson |accessdate= 8 January 2016}}</ref><ref name="lwn-app-sandbox-revisited">{{cite news | last=Willis | first=Nathan | date=2015-01-21 |title=GNOME and application sandboxing revisited | url=https://lwn.net/Articles/630216/ | newspaper=LWN | access-date=2016-01-03}}</ref> Applications using Flatpak need permission from the user to control hardware devices or access the user's files.<ref>{{cite news | last=Willis | first=Nathan | date=2015-08-12 | title=Working with xdg-app application bundles | url=https://lwn.net/Articles/654128/ | newspaper=LWN | access-date=2016-01-03}}</ref>
The idea of using application containers in GNOME was first proposed in 2013 by [[Lennart Poettering]],<ref name="lwn-app-sandbox-revisited" /> who published an article about it in 2014.<ref name="Poettering">{{Cite web|url=https://lwn.net/Articles/610067/|title=Poettering: Revisiting how we put together Linux systems|author=corbet|date=1 September 2014|website=LWN|access-date=2016-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Lennart|last=Poettering|author-link=Lennart Poettering |date=1 September 2014 |title= Revisiting How We Put Together Linux Systems |website=Pid Eins |url=http://0pointer.net/blog/revisiting-how-we-put-together-linux-systems.html }}</ref> Developed as part of the [[freedesktop.org]] project (formerly known as X Desktop Group or XDG),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flatpak.org|title=Flatpak - the future of application distribution|accessdate=2016-12-16}}</ref> it was originally called ''xdg-app''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lists.freedesktop.org/archives/xdg-app/2016-May/000204.html |title=Renamed to flatpak in git |website=freedesktop.org|date=9 May 2016 |first=Alexander |last=Larsson |accessdate= 1 June 2016}}</ref>
{{As of|2017|02}}, some popular apps available as Flatpaks include [[Blender (software)|Blender]], [[GIMP|Gimp]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gimp.org/downloads/|title=GIMP - Downloads|website=www.gimp.org}}</ref> [[LibreOffice]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.libreoffice.org/download/flatpak/ |title=LibreOffice in Flatpak format |website=LibreOffice |date= |author= |accessdate= 1 June 2016}}</ref> [[Pitivi]],<ref name="pitivi-download">{{cite web|url=http://www.pitivi.org/?go=download|title=Pitivi-download|website=Pitivi|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> [[KDE Applications]],<ref name="kde-applications">{{cite web|url=https://community.kde.org/Guidelines_and_HOWTOs/Flatpak|title=kde-applications|website=KDE Flatpak|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref> [[Linphone]],<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.linphone.org/#features |title=Linphone |accessdate=2017-09-19}}</ref> and [[GNOME Recipes]].<ref>{{Cite web| last = Sneddon| first = Joey| title = Yum! GNOME Recipes is a New Cooking App for Linux| work = OMG! Ubuntu!| accessdate = 2017-12-24| date = 2016-12-07| url = http://www.omgubuntu.co.uk/2016/12/gnome-desktop-cooking-app}}</ref> There are also some unofficial Flatpaks such as development versions of [[Mozilla Firefox]],<ref name="firefox-flatpak">{{cite web|url=https://firefox-flatpak.mojefedora.cz/|title=Unofficial Firefox Developer Edition flatpak repository|website=Unofficial Firefox Developer Edition flatpak repository|accessdate=20 March 2017}}</ref> [[Skype]],<ref name="skype-flatpak">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/alexlarsson/skype-app/|title=Alexander Larsson's github Flatpak build of skype|website=Alexander Larsson's github Flatpak build of skype|accessdate=17 August 2017}}</ref> and [[Spotify]].<ref name="spotify-flatpak">{{cite web|url=https://github.com/alexlarsson/spotify-app/|title=Alexander Larsson's github Flatpak build of spotify|website=Alexander Larsson's github Flatpak build of spotify|accessdate=17 August 2017}}</ref>
